Hi everyone, as of 29/08/22, if you are at 2:33:00 to 2:55:00 in the video and are working with the SIngleRoom page / component, you will likely run into a problem where your component will not display when you re-run your app. Like in my previous comment, this issue comes from changes in the newest version of React Router. The new version will not pass props to the class component by default like what was done in the tutorial.  My solution to this issue was to change the class component into a functional component and use React and React Router hooks. 

I have added all the code in SingleRoom.js that should fix the issue at this point in the video (along with some comments explaining the process):

------- SingleRoom.js ---------
// import the useContext hook from 'react', no need for Component since we are using an RFC
import React, { useContext} from 'react'
import defaultBcg from '../images/room-1.jpeg'
import Hero from '../components/Hero'
import Banner from '../components/Banner'

// import the useParams hook from React Router
import {Link, useParams} from 'react-router-dom'
import { RoomContext } from '../context'

// Transform the RCC to an RFC
export default function SingleRoom() {
    // Get the slug using React Router's useParams hook
    const { slug } = useParams();
    
    // Get the context we defined in context.js using React's useContext hook
    const context = useContext(RoomContext);

    // Similar to the tutorial, we access the getRoom function through our context (no need for 'this')
    const { getRoom } = context;

    // Get the room object that matches our slug like in the tutorial (no need to access state)
    const room = getRoom(slug);

    // Other than no longer needing the render function, everything else should be the same as in the tutorial
    if (!room){
      return <div className='error'>
        <h3>no such room could be found</h3>
        <Link to='/rooms' className='btn-primary'>
          back to rooms
        </Link>
      </div>
    }
    const {name, description, capacity, size, price, extras, breakfast, pets, images} = room;
    return (
      <Hero hero='roomsHero'>
        <Banner title={`${name} room`}>
          <Link to="/rooms" className='btn-primary'>
            back to rooms
          </Link>
        </Banner>
      </Hero>
    )
  }

Hope this helps! It seems the latest trend in React is to use functional components instead of class components in many places, filling in any functionality gaps with hooks. Another thing to learn, but arguably very important for the future of building in React!

Hi everyone, as of 27/08/22, if you are at 30:30 to 38:30 in the video and are adding routes using React Router, you likely will run into an error where text (AKA your components) wont display when you re-run your app. The issue comes from changes in the newest versions of React Router. Other comments below had solutions that helped me, but I thought I would go a step further and show all the code in App.js and index.js that should fix this issue at this point in the video:

------ App.js ------
import React from "react"
import './App.css';
import Home from "./pages/Home";
import Rooms from "./pages/Rooms";
import SingleRoom from "./pages/SingleRoom";
import Error from "./pages/Error";
import { Routes, Route } from "react-router-dom";

function App() {
  return (
    <>
      <Navbar />
      <Routes> 
        <Route exact path="/" element={<Home/>}/>
        <Route exact path="/rooms" element={ <Rooms/>}/>
        <Route exact path="/rooms/:slug" element={<SingleRoom/>}/>     
        <Route path="*" element={ <Error/>}/>
      </Routes>
    </>
  );
}

export default App;


-----  index.js ----
import React from 'react';
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom/client';
// import './index.css';
import App from './App';
import { BrowserRouter as Router } from 'react-router-dom';

const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(
  document.getElementById("root")
);

root.render(
  <Router>
    <App />    
  </Router>
);

Later on when you encounter <Link to="/"> for instance, it should still work as it did when this tutorial first came out. Once you are around 2:33:00, you will run into another issue with the new version of React Router not passing props to the class component by default. I detailed my solution to this issue in another comment.

Hope this helps!

